---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Magritte — a keyboard-first Git client for macOS"
  description="Magritte is a fast, keyboard-first Git client inspired by Magit: the status-centered workflow as a standalone macOS app, no Emacs required."
>
  <h1>Magritte</h1>
  <p class="tagline"><em>Ceci n'est pas Magit.</em></p>

  <p class="lede">
    A fast, keyboard-first Git client for macOS, inspired by
    <a href="https://magit.vc/">Magit</a>. The status view shows the whole
    repository; move to a file, hunk, or commit and act on it. Commands such as
    commit, branch, push, and rebase open focused menus that show their
    options. No Emacs required.
  </p>

  <pre class="install"><code>brew install lyallcooper/magritte/magritte</code></pre>

  <div class="window">
    <span class="dot red"></span><span class="dot yellow"></span><span class="dot green"></span>
    <picture>
      <source
        srcset="/screenshots/status-dark-mobile.png"
        media="(max-width: 40rem) and (prefers-color-scheme: dark)"
      />
      <source srcset="/screenshots/status-light-mobile.png" media="(max-width: 40rem)" />
      <source srcset="/screenshots/status-dark.png" media="(prefers-color-scheme: dark)" />
      <img
        src="/screenshots/status-light.png"
        width="730"
        height="702"
        alt="Magritte's status view on its own repository: untracked, unstaged, and staged sections, an expanded file diff with a syntax-highlighted hunk, and recent commits"
      />
    </picture>
  </div>

  <h2>One view, acted on at point</h2>
  <p>
    Everything starts from the status view. <kbd>Tab</kbd> unfolds the item at
    the cursor — a file into its diff, a section into its contents. Commands
    apply to the item at point: <kbd>s</kbd> stages the current hunk when the
    cursor is on a hunk, the file when it is on a file, the whole section when
    it is on a heading. Visual selection applies an action to several rows at
    once.
  </p>

  <div class="keys">
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>j</kbd> / <kbd>k</kbd></span> Move down or up</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>c</kbd></span> Commit menu</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>Tab</kbd></span> Expand or collapse</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>b</kbd></span> Branch menu</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>s</kbd> / <kbd>u</kbd></span> Stage or unstage</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>p</kbd> / <kbd>F</kbd></span> Push or pull menu</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>x</kbd></span> Discard (confirmed)</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>l</kbd></span> Log menu</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>:</kbd></span> Search all commands</div>
    <div><span class="k"><kbd>?</kbd></span> Commands and their keys</div>
  </div>

  <h2>If you know Magit</h2>
  <p>
    You already know Magritte. The default keymap follows
    evil-collection-magit; a vanilla Emacs/Magit preset is one setting away.
    Transient menus, act-at-point, section folding, and the safety
    confirmations work the way Magit's do — where behavior differs, it is
    documented. <a href="https://github.com/lyallcooper/magritte/blob/main/docs/dev/magit-parity.md">Magit parity</a>
    lists what is supported and what is missing, feature by feature.
  </p>

  <h2>Configuration</h2>
  <p>
    Themes, fonts, and the keymap preset live in the Settings screen
    (<kbd>,</kbd>). Everything else — key remapping, custom commands, status
    sections, background fetching, transient menu changes — is a TOML file that
    reloads on save, with an optional per-repository overlay. See the
    <a href="/docs/config/">configuration guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Status</h2>
  <p>Magritte is under active development. Current limitations:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>macOS on Apple silicon is the supported release target; Linux x86_64 builds are best effort.</li>
    <li>Release builds are ad hoc signed, not notarized.</li>
    <li>Requires <code>git</code> on your <code>PATH</code>; it refreshes on focus and after its own commands rather than watching the filesystem.</li>
  </ul>
</Base>

<style>
  .tagline {
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .lede {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    max-width: 40rem;
  }

  .install {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  /* The status-view screenshot, framed as the window it was captured from.
     The offscreen capture omits the native traffic lights; the title bar
     leaves their standard inset, so CSS dots restore them. */
  .window {
    position: relative;
    container-type: inline-size;
    margin: 2rem 0 0.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 9px;
    overflow: hidden;
    box-shadow: 0 12px 32px -12px rgb(0 0 0 / 0.25);
    line-height: 0;
  }

  .window img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }

  /* Sized in cqw so the dots track the screenshot's title bar (33 logical px
     tall at a natural width of 730) as the image scales. */
  .dot {
    position: absolute;
    top: 1.44cqw;
    width: 1.64cqw;
    height: 1.64cqw;
    border-radius: 50%;
  }

  .dot.red { left: 1.92cqw; background: #ec6a5e; }
  .dot.yellow { left: 4.66cqw; background: #f4bf4f; }
  .dot.green { left: 7.4cqw; background: #61c554; }

  /* The mobile capture is 640 logical px wide (vs 730), so the title bar is
     proportionally taller; rescale the dots to it. */
  @media (max-width: 40rem) {
    .dot {
      top: 1.64cqw;
      width: 1.88cqw;
      height: 1.88cqw;
    }

    .dot.red { left: 2.19cqw; }
    .dot.yellow { left: 5.31cqw; }
    .dot.green { left: 8.44cqw; }
  }

  /* Key reference: two columns where they fit, one on narrow screens */
  .keys {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(17rem, 1fr));
    column-gap: 3rem;
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 1rem 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .keys > div {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    align-items: baseline;
    padding: 0.35rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .keys .k {
    flex: 0 0 4.5rem;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }
</style>
